{"cursor":"3487","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox royalty\n| type = monarch name = OrdoÃ±o III image = Ordono III of LeÃ³n.jpg imgw = 200px\n| caption = Later medieval depiction of OrdoÃ±o III succession = King of LeÃ³n\n| reign = 951–956 coronation = predecessor = Ramiro II successor = Sancho\n| I spouse = Urraca FernÃ¡ndez issue =OrdoÃ±o Theresa Bermudo II of LeÃ³n\n| issue-link = issue-pipe = full name = house = Beni Alfons house-type = Dynasty\n| father = Ramiro II of LeÃ³n mother = Adosinda GutiÃ©rrez birth_date = c. 925\n| birth_place = death_date = c. 956 death_place = Zamora burial_place = Basilica\n| of San Isidoro religion = Roman Catholicism }}\n\n'OrdoÃ±o III' (–956) was the King of LeÃ³n from 951 to 956, son and\nsuccessor of Ramiro II\n(931–951). http://thepeerage.com/p15273.htm#i152726 He\nconfronted Navarre and Castile, who supported his half-brother Sancho the Fat in\ndisputing OrdoÃ±o's claim to the throne.\n\nHe also had to deal with internal rebellion, attacks from the Muslims of al-\nAndalus, and the rebellion of Galicia. In response to the Muslims, OrdoÃ±o III\nled a raid as far as Lisbon (955), coming back north with a very lucrative\nloot. Faced with this great show of force, Abd-al-Rahman III\n(912–961) was pushed to negotiate and conclude a peace treaty with the\nking of LeÃ³n.\n\nHe tried to continue the actions of his father in fortifying the land and the\nroyal authority in the face of the contumacious and secessional FernÃ¡n GonzÃ¡lez\nof Castile. He even married FernÃ¡n's daughter Urraca and later repudiated her\nover her father's alliance with Sancho.\n\nUrraca bore him at least two children: a son named OrdoÃ±o who died young and a\ndaughter named Theresa who became a nun. OrdoÃ±o III was also father of Bermudo\nII, but opinion is divided as to whether he was son of Urraca, or of a mistress,\none of the daughters of Count Pelayo Gonzalez.\n\nOrdoÃ±o III died at Zamora in 956.\n","linknr":148,"url":"Ordoñ